<article class="consulting-field-note" id="main">
  <!-- LW: the last frame-bender -->
  <section class="consulting-flow" aria-label="Consulting copy">
    <div class="consulting-block consulting-block--lead" data-label="perspective">
      <p>After enough time around the workings of organizations, tools, and human judgment, I&rsquo;ve found myself at a <span class="consulting-tooltip"><a class="consulting-quiet-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_point" aria-label="Lagrange point: close enough to feel the pull of things, far enough away to see what&rsquo;s happening." data-note="Close enough to feel the pull of things, far enough away to see what&rsquo;s happening.">Lagrange point</a></span> between disciplines and perspectives. That vantage is what I bring.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="consulting-block" data-label="tools">
      <p>I&rsquo;ve borrowed a suite of useful &ldquo;tools&rdquo; along the way, and made a few of my own. Over time, I&rsquo;ve learned the difference between a tool-shaped problem and a human-shaped problem.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="consulting-block consulting-block--payoff" data-label="frame">
      <p>In complicated work, people often already know more than they can say. What&rsquo;s usually needed is to bend the frame: to see the same thing differently. Bending the frame well, with a human touch, is a skill. That&rsquo;s why you pay me.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="consulting-block consulting-principles" data-label="principles" aria-label="Principles">
      <dl class="consulting-principles-list">
        <div class="consulting-principle">
          <dt>Public interest</dt>
          <dd>Attention to who might have to live with the results of our work together.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="consulting-principle">
          <dt>Hospitality</dt>
          <dd>Attention to service, in the craft sense: presence, timing, and care.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="consulting-principle">
          <dt>Craft</dt>
          <dd>Attention to materials, constraints, finish, and use.</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-block consulting-arrangement" data-label="arrangement" aria-label="How consulting starts">
      <p>Send me a short or long note about what you&rsquo;re working on. Email or DM is fine. I&rsquo;ll ask follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better we can decide, and the better I can research/prepare if we want to move forward.</p>

      <p>If we both think there&rsquo;s something worth doing, the next step is a paid &ldquo;thought sparring&rdquo; conversation: $350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call. I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The purpose of the call is to bend the frame on your problem, and to give you a sense of whether you&rsquo;re <a class="consulting-quiet-link" href="https://stephango.com/in-good-hands">in good hands</a>.</p>

      <p>I only book the call if I&rsquo;m confident I can deliver more than $350 in value to you. If I can&rsquo;t, I&rsquo;ll tell you, and where I can, point you to someone who fits better.</p>

      <p>If we want to keep going past the first call, scope and rate are something we agree on in writing.</p>
    </section>
  </section>
</article>
